===Preposition===
{{head|la|preposition}}

# {{context|with accusative|direction|lang=la}} [[toward]], [[to]], [[up to]]
#* {{Q|la|Lucretius|De rerum natura|4|quote=Fugere '''ad''' puppim colles campique videntur.|trans=The hills and fields appear to fly '''toward''' the ship.}}
#* {{Q|la|Pliny the Elder|Naturalis Historia|2|quote=Meridie umbrae cadunt '''ad''' septentrionem, ortu vero '''ad''' occasum.|trans=At noon the shadows fall '''towards''' the north, [and] at sunrise, point '''to''' the west.}}
#* {{Q|la|Virgil|Aeneid|1|93|quote=Duplices tendens '''ad''' sidera palmas.|trans=Stretching both hands '''to''' the stars.}}
#: {{usex|lang=la|'''Ad''' vim atque [[ad arma|'''ad''' arma]] confugere.|t=To fly '''to''' violence and '''to''' fighting.}}

====Related terms====
* [[ad-]] (same word modified and used as a prefix)

====Usage notes====
* The word '''ad''' is an [[antithesis]] to {{term|ab|lang=la}} (just as {{term|in|lang=la}} is to {{term|ex|lang=la}}; in a progressive order of relation, {{term|ad|lang=la}} denotes, first, the direction toward an object; then the reaching of or attaining to it; and finally, the being at or near it.)
* Often used of geographical position of a place in reference to the points of compass, with the verbs {{m|la|iaceō||lie, be situated}}, {{m|la|vergō||incline, slope}}, {{m|la|spectō||observe, see}} etc.:
*: ''Asia iacet '''ad''' meridiem et austrum, Europa '''ad''' septentriones et aquilonem.''
*:: Asia lies '''near''' the prime meridian and the south, Europe '''near''' the northern regions and northern wind. (two words for north)
*: '''''Ad''' Atticam vergente.''
*:: Inclining '''to''' Attic.
* When appended to the beginning of a word, ''ad'' often becomes {{term|ap-|lang=la}} when followed by ‘p’, as in {{m|la|appretiō}}, from {{term|pretium|lang=la}}.  But note that {{m|la|adpretiō}} is also found.

